Leyline & Lunacy: How Two Idiots Nearly Got Themselves Erased From Reality

Arkne

Morning comes reluctantly to Arkne, as it always does. He cracks open his grey eyes with the same enthusiasm one reserves for tax audits, watching the pale light filter through the high dormitory windows. The water temples bells toll faintly in the distanceQujjas call. He exhales through his nose, rubs the sleep from his eyes, and rises with the stiff grace of someone whod rather be horizontal.

 

The gloves go on first, always. Soft black leather, well-fitted, never removed except in absolute solitude. No one needs to know what stains these hands carry. The rest of his attire followslight scholars robes, crisply pressed, embroidered with gold thread that catches the predawn light. Practical, presentable. Not that he cares much for appearances, but nobility demands its petty sacrifices.

 

Tea is necessary. Arkne sets a kettle to boil over the small brazier in his room, grinding dried herbs between his fingers. He doesnt need to ward the door shutthe other students learned quickly that knocking before noon is a poor life decisionbut he does it anyway. Old habits.

 

His morning lectures pass in a blur of dry academia and stifled yawns. He tolerates the chatter of his peers with the patience of a man counting to tenand then to twenty, just to be safe. Occasionally, someone glances at his gloved hands and asks, as if it hasnt been asked a hundred times before:

 

Why the gloves, Helsberg?

 

Arkne doesnt pause in taking notes. Contrary to rumor, I dont have claws. Just an abiding hatred for ink stains. His tone is smooth, bored, daring the asker to press further. They never do.

 

He ducks the midday meal in favor of the library, where shadowed stacks offer more companionship than the dining halls din. A tome on advanced Mysth theory lies open before him, finger tracing the lines as he memorizes the patterns. A quill moves in slow, precise arcs beside itnotes for a paper, perhaps, or something less academic.

 

By evening, hes back in his dorm, stirring a pot over a small, warded fire. Stewed herbs, roasted meat, the scent trapped neatly within his wards. Youd think scholars would have something better to do than sniff at doors. Meadr knocks exactly twice before barging in, as is their arrangement, and the rare, faint warmth in Arknes expression isnt just from the steam.

 

Dont hover, he says, nudging a bowl toward his friend. Its not poisoned. Probably.

 

Meadr

Probably? Meadr repeats, flashing a warm, lopsided grin as he takes the proffered bowl. His golden eyes crinkle at the edgesfoxlike, though he only lets that resemblance slip when alone. He lifts the stew to his nose, inhaling deeply before sighing appreciatively. Ah, theres the real reason I tolerate you. A noble who can actually cook.

 

He perches on the edge of Arknes desk, bowl balanced neatly between both hands, posture relaxed but subtly angled toward the doorhabit. The enchanted necklace weighs nothing against his collarbone, yet its presence hums in his awareness as always. Safe. Contained.

 

Between spoonfuls, he nods toward Arknes glovestodays pair a deep, inky black. Ink stains, hm? I figured it was just your usual flair for dramatics. Next youll tell me you sleep with them on. He tilts his head, smirk dancing at the corner of his lips. Unless you do, in which case, well, thats between you and your tailor.

 

Meadrs tone is airy, teasing, but his fingers flex slightly over the bowl. The topic is familiar, like an old dancean offhand joke masking genuine curiosity beneath. He knows better than to press (they both have their reasons for secrets), but the question lingers in the lilt of his voice.

 

When Arkne inevitably deflects again, hell let it go. He always does. For now, he nudges the conversation along with a safer subject, gesturing toward the open tome on the desk. Still pouring over those leyline theories? Or just preparing another lecture to put the underclassmen to sleep? His grin widensa dare. Rhezua might actually fight you if you upstage her again in Mysth Law.

 

Arkne

Arkne scoffs, stirring the pot with deliberate laziness before turning to fix Meadr with a look that could freeze a lesser man in place. Sleeping in gloves? Please. Even my dramatics have standards. He lifts the spoon, inspecting it with exaggerated scrutiny. And here I thought you had at least some sense of decency, Meadr. First you barge into my room, then you suggest I wear my gloves to bed like some kind of paranoid hermit.

 

He ladles a generous portion of stew into Meadrs bowlbecause despite his tone, the redhead knows him well enough to recognize this as a silent stay, I dont entirely despise your company.

 

At the mention of Rhezua, his lip twitchesthough whether in amusement or annoyance is difficult to tell. Ah yes, Rhezua. The great tragedy of her existence is that I exist first. A sardonic sip of his own tea. If she wants to challenge me in Mysth Law, shes welcome to try. Its hardly my fault the Obott cursed her with less competent tutors.

 

He eyes the open tome, expression shifting to something contemplativecloser to his true self than the mask of detached arrogance. Leyline mapping, actually. Theres a hypothesis in the Northern Archives about using minor nexus points as temporary wards. Faster than chanting, more precise than weaving. If I can

 

He cuts himself off abruptly, as if catching the rare slip of enthusiasm before it could be fully exposed. Clearing his throat, he flicks a speck of nonexistent dust off his sleeve, mouth settling back into its usual mild disinterest.

 

Anyway. You wouldnt care. Historys more your specialty. A pause, then, with just the barest hint of dry amusement: Unless youre finally taking an interest in practical applications beyond which leyline makes the best shortcut back from festivals?

 

Meadr

Meadr lets out a warm laugh, the kind that lingers like sunlight in a quiet room. Cursed her with less competent tutors, he says, he echoes, shaking his head. You do realize you sound like the antagonist in half the ballads they sing in the lower quarters, dont you? Next you'll be monologuing about the insufferable mediocrity of peasantry.

 

He swirls the stew in his bowl, leaning forward just slightly. Arknes rare flickers of unchecked interest never escape himhe catalogues them like prized artifacts. Leyline wards, huh? Sounds useful. Especially if they could be deployed mid-conflict without all that tedious chanting. A pause, then a playful smirk. Though I did hear that Demr managed to singe his eyebrows off trying something similar last week. Maybe dont skip the chants entirely.

 

The mention of shortcuts earns another grin, though his fingers brush the hollow of his throat absentlyhabit. Festival routes are practical applications, thank you very much. Not all of us enjoy looming over books like brooding specters. He tilts his head. But if youre desperate for a field test, I suppose I could be convinced to scout a nexus point with you. Provided you dont plan to blow anything up. Or lecture me about proper academic rigor while we walk.

 

He takes a deliberate bite, chewing slowly before adding, softer: Besides. If Rhezuas watching, itll annoy her twice as much if youve got company. His tone is light, but the offer is genuine beneath the teasinga carefully crafted opening, just ambiguous enough to retreat from if Arkne bristles.

 

Arkne

Arkne arches a brow, stirring his tea with the air of a man who absolutely does loom over books like a brooding specterand enjoys it. Field tests are for scholars who lack the imagination to conduct proper research indoors, he mutters, though there's a flicker of consideration in his gaze. ...But if your delicate festival sensibilities require fresh air, I suppose I could sacrifice an afternoon. For science.

 

A pause. A sip. Then, dry as parchment: And Demr singeing his eyebrows off was inevitable. The man tries to weave Mysth like hes tossing grain to pigeons. His lips twitchalmost a smile, if one squinted. Rest assured, I have no intentions of resembling a partially plucked songbird. Unlike some.

Then, quieter: Bring bread. The dense kind. If were testing wards, you might as well be useful.

 

Meadr

Meadr beamsan expression just shy of triumphant, the sort that could make a cynic believe in sunshine. Aha! So you do admit fresh air has its merits, he teases, pointing his spoon in Arknes direction with playful accusation. Dont worry, Ill protect your scholarly dignity from the horrors of grass and sky. His voice drops to a stage whisper, eyes glinting. And if anyone asks, we can say you were lured outside against your will. Kidnapped by a rogue historian with a terrifying surplus of charm.

 

The mention of Demrs mishap earns a snort. Bread is an easy promise. Meadr nods, already mentally rifling through the bakery stalls near the institutes eastern gate. Dense loaf, got it. Anything to spare the world the tragic sight of Arkne Helsberg, felled by low blood sugar mid-ward. He taps his chin. Should I pack honey too? Or would that be too decadent for field research?

 

Beneath the banter, though, he catches the near-smilethe unspoken concessionand files it away like a rare tome. Hell burn this moment to memory later, alone in his room, when the necklace comes off and his thoughts dare to wander. For now, he merely nudges Arknes boot with his own under the desk, fleeting and deliberate.

 

Dont look so dour. Who knows? Maybe well uncover a leyline that leads straight to a hidden cache of first-edition Eltherion Scrolls. His grin turns conspiratorial. ...Or at least a shortcut to that bakery that sells the spiced fig tarts.

 

Arkne

Tarts, Arkne echoes, in the same tone one might use to describe a particularly gruesome tax audit. Because nothing says groundbreaking academic research like pastries. I can already see the thesis title'On the Correlation Between Leyline Flux and the Optimal Flakiness of Baked Goods.' Truly, Meadr, your scholarly rigor paralyzes me with awe.

 

He rolls his eyes butdamn himtheres no real bite to it. His fingers drum once against the desk before he abruptly snaps the tome shut, as if belatedly remembering hes supposed to be aloof. Fine. Bring your tarts. But if this expedition devolves into yet another of your scenic detours, I will leave you in the nearest leyline nexus as an impromptu Mysth conductor.

 

A pause. Then, with the air of a man reluctantly admitting defeat: And pack extra honey. For He gestures vaguely, nearly knocking over his tea. Contingencies.

 

(He does not specify what kind. Meadr will know. Meadr always knows.)

 

Meadr

Meadr leans back, shoulders shaking with silent laughtereyes alight with the kind of mischief that made lesser nobles sigh and professors take measured, cautious steps backward. Oh, obviously, he drawls, sweeping a dramatic hand across an imaginary title page. 'A Sweetener's Guide to Leylines: Saccharine Solutions for the Academic Soul.' Groundbreaking, really. I expect an honorary professorship by week's end.

 

His boots drop from the desk with a soft thud as he straightens, fingers brushing briefly against his hidden necklaceonce, like a talismanbefore he mock-salutes Arkne. Scenic detour? Me? Never. The grin softens at the edges, betraying his sincerity. But just in caseI'll leave a trail of breadcrumbs. Honeyed ones, naturally. He pauses at the door, tossing a final look over his shouldergolden eyes glinting like summer-warmed copper in the dim light. Until tomorrow, then. Try not to fret too much about it. Wouldnt want you showing up over-prepared. The teasing is deliberate, barbless. A familiar dance.

 

(He will, of course, pack extra honey. He always does.)

 

Alddm, Arkne. The door clicks shut behind him, muffling the hum of his laughterleaving behind only the faintest lingering scent of cinnamon and something earthier, warmer.

 

 

 

Arkne

Arkne watches the door close for a beat too long before returning to his research. The candlelight flickers across his impassive face as he scribbles notes with one hand and absently stirs the cooling tea with the other.

 

Leylines and fig tarts, he mutters under his breath with a quiet scoff. What fresh academic hell have I agreed to?

 

Yet his fingers pause mid-sentence, hovering over the page where he'd been detailing ward schematics. After a moment, he flips to a fresh sheet andwith deliberate, precise strokesbegins sketching a rough map of the nearest accessible leyline nexus, marking potential shortcuts to the bakery district in the margins with far more thoroughness than strictly necessary.

 

For contingencies.

 

Arkne

The path to the nearest leyline nexus winds through the eastern ridge of the Arx valley, where early morning fog still clings stubbornly between the pines. (It includes the bakery detour. Obviously.)

 

Meadr

Meadr doesn't specify. He's always preferred leaving room for interpretation.
